        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la" resp="#AA">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" key="augustus"><name>Aug<supplied reason="lost">us</supplied>to</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><expan><abbr>sacr</abbr><ex>um</ex></expan>
                    <lb n="3"/>Perusia restituta
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text from autopsy</note></app> 
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>Sacred to Augustus, Perusia having been restored.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>One of four almost identical altar-shaped stones from Perusia, all with near identical inscriptions: Augusto | sacr(um) | Perusia | restituta (see also <ref target="EmpWor000495.xml">EmpWor000495</ref>, <ref target="EmpWor000496.xml">EmpWor000496</ref>, and <ref target="EmpWor000498.xml">EmpWor000498</ref>). It is possible (and this is the possibility that I prefer), that these four boundary-stones demarcated the boundaries of the lucus ('sacred grove') of <ref target="EmpWor000494.xml">EmpWor000494</ref>. The boundary stones make it obvious why the sacred grove was dedicated to Augustus: he had restored their community after its destruction after the so-called Perusine War of 41–40 BCE. Spadoni and Benedetti (2010, 221) suggest that the lucus may have been architectural (and surrounded by a grove), but also suggest (221–223) that the boundary stones may have had some other purpose, for instance in delimiting the borders of the ager Perusinus or the pomerium of Perusia.</p> 
            </div>
